  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3697941614" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3697941614" />
    <a title="Dillwynia Peter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8394997-dillwynia-peter"><img alt="Dillwynia Peter" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1332831047p2/8394997.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3697941614?book_show_action=true">Dec 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dillwynia Peter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dillwynia Peter" href="/user/show/8394997-dillwynia-peter">Dillwynia Peter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3697941614" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8528767219538209857">“Fated boy!” – those words said by Captain Vere had my heart in my mouth, in horror, as I realised, we were going to rapidly descend into a dramatic end. This multi-layered novella packs a punch, and it hurts, and it doesn’t hold back.<br/><br/>A story of suppressed desires, jealousies, and control: all confined to a small space, where there is nowhere to escape. It’s a leaking powder keg that has a spitting match swinging above. From the time Billy Budd is press ganged, his story is one of doom and extre</span>
  <span id="freeText8528767219538209857" style="display:none">“Fated boy!” – those words said by Captain Vere had my heart in my mouth, in horror, as I realised, we were going to rapidly descend into a dramatic end. This multi-layered novella packs a punch, and it hurts, and it doesn’t hold back.<br /><br />A story of suppressed desires, jealousies, and control: all confined to a small space, where there is nowhere to escape. It’s a leaking powder keg that has a spitting match swinging above. From the time Billy Budd is press ganged, his story is one of doom and extreme expectations. The merchant captain regards Budd as his peacemaker, and the Lieutenant has the concept that his trait will be useful on the warship. Much has been written on this book, so I will concentrate on what interested me as I processed this gem.<br /><br />This novel is riddled with allegory, ironies, and oxymorons. A peacemaker entering the service of an active warship! starts it off. I want to concentrate on the character’s names, for I think they are onomatopoeic to their traits. Captain Vere – a nobleman, so severe (Sir Vere); Claggart = Blaggart; Billy Budd; Squeak – the person who is going to inform to Claggart, and thinks he can “squeak” information out of Budd. The two ship’s names: Bellepotent – strong in war; Rights of Man – the antithesis to a warship, especially those sailors on the warship who have been impressed and have lost their rights.<br /><br />Captain Vere – a man who can be a martinet when it comes to authority. In this case, he allowed an incident to happen in his cabin, and worse, he is uncertain whether the scent of mutiny is just a japed charge made up by Claggart, or has he actually started something, such that with his violent death, it may be acted out. Budd is the scapegoat, and to hide as much of the evidence from ruining Vere’s career, he sacrifices Budd to naval law. Vere is a complex character in that in one aspect there is affection and friendship in his attitude, but he mires himself in his inflated sense of honour and personal worth.<br /><br />Claggart is a victim, but in a different way. He shares with Budd a hidden past; we know almost all of the pedigree of Vere, but Claggart is a mystery. He comes from no known family or relationship; a patron or family connection was absolutely necessary to rise within the ranks of the navy. There are very veiled hints that Claggart sees Budd as a younger version of himself. However, there has been failure in Claggart’s life, and he is bitter against the system. In rolls Budd, and he sees the opportunities that either were denied or fell foul. Whatever, his jealousies overrule any intelligent reasoning or reckoning. Petty unfettered or controlled actions are instigated, with a sole purpose of removing Budd from the ship, and turning him from the naïve innocent character he is, into a villain. Claggart is a villain, and a bully, but he is also the personification of war: senseless violence that is condoned via the naval social system, but which produces no positive outcome. I developed a sense of pity for Claggart: the system had moulded him into the individual he was; an individual totally unsuited to civilian life, and the joys of an adulthood such as love and relationships. In a way, he is belatedly fighting against the system.<br /><br />Billy Budd I equate with a flower bud: innocence and full of potential. Emotionally, Budd is very naïve and innocent. He is definitely someone who can not read the emotions being bandied in a room. He completely misconstrues the anger and vitriol delivered by Claggart over a spill from a bowl of soup. Others see the latent potential in Budd, and manipulate his accordingly; however, Budd might be naïve, he most certainly is neither simple nor stupid. Claggart makes that error in a classic go-between; but just as Rosencrantz &amp; Guildenstern fail in manipulating Hamlet, so too Claggart’s attempts are clumpsy, although Budd almost falls for them. Budd is Adam before the Tree of Knowledge; his fall however, is fatal, and with is fall are the destruction of others as listed in the prologue.<br /><br />I noticed the latent and heavy homoerotic aspect to the book. Melville liked to explore gender and sexuality and was aware of homosexual behaviours and acceptances in the Navy. Billy Budd is not his only novel to openly challenge the reader. I’ve read many 19th century novels where a handsome male is described in depth, adding sexual overtones, but this was very different. The descriptions in the early pages of the book were sensual and akin to how a man would describe a very beautiful woman. Even Budd’s popularity has a hint of sensuality and sex appeal about it in the descriptions. This homoerotism adds to the frisson between Claggart and Budd. Is there unattainable love here? Is Claggart concerned with his reputation as a junior officer and any option for promotion, if he submits to any sexual feelings? This angle was explored by Britten’s opera Billy Budd, and I found this angle very believable from the text. Did Melville intend this? We can’t know.<br /><br />I ponder as to why Melville didn’t publish this during his lifetime. Was this a story that had inner meanings to him, reminding him of events of his time in the US Navy? Was this a way of letting him express a form of homosexuality that he personally, and thus a private book, almost a diary, such as Forster’s Maurice? Was it a response to the international growing warmongering, particularly in Europe? Arms races were common and displayed at the time of writing, and this story definitely makes him an individualist and pacifist. All unknowable.<br /><br />The style is somewhat dry and laden with a pompous syntax. It reminded me of Henry James at his worst. The younger writers were doing Modernist things to books, in style at least at a complete polar opposite, and maybe he felt his writing was an anachronism and not likely to get published anyway; and maybe, just maybe he had been burnt enough by previous critics that he didn’t want to feel their nasty barbs anymore.<br /><br />The style and syntax may be off putting to some, but plough through – because this gem says an awful lot about mankind in a very brief and succinct way. I’m pleased I made the effort.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8528767219538209857" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


